[This report has good news and not-so-good news. The good news is that once again there were no AFP (acute flaccid paralysis) cases associated with WPV1 (wild poliovirus type 1) infection, nor were there any environmental samples positive for WPV1.

The not-so-good news is the continued outbreaks associated with cVDPV (circulating vaccine-derived polioviruses), at present exclusively cVDPV2 (type 2 cVDPV: 7 countries have identified new AFP cases associated with cVDPV2 infections, and an additional 2 countries identified cVDPV2 in environmental samples. (Note that Burkina Faso reported 2 cases with date of onset in 2020 and Niger reported 1 case with date of onset in 2020.) Hence, at least 7 countries are represented with active transmission/circulation of cVDPV2. Other not-so-good news is the recurrence of violence against polio vaccinators and their protectors (see sections [2] and [3] below), leading to cessation of vaccination activities in Pakistan and Afghanistan where the WPV1 is under cover but present, as evidenced by a positive environmental sample for WPV1 reported in last week's update (Poliomyelitis update (10): Senegal, cVDPV2 20210614.8447598). - Mod.MPP]

******
[2] Afghanistan - violence against vaccinators
[2A] UN statement
Date: Tue 15 Jun 2021
Source: Global Polio Eradication initiative [edited]
https://afghanistan.un.org/en/131465-statement-attacks-polio-workers-dr-ramiz-alakbarov-united-nations-dsrsg-resident-and


Statement on attacks on polio workers - Dr. Ramiz Alakbarov, United Nations DSRSG, Resident and Humanitarian Coordinator
--------------------
Health workers in 5 locations in Nangarhar province were attacked today [Tue 15 Jun 2021] during the course of their life-saving work; 5 were killed, and 4 were injured in 5 separate incidents.

I extend my deepest condolences to the families, friends, and colleagues of those who lost their lives and wish those who are injured a full and swift recovery.

I am appalled by the brutality of these killings. This is not the 1st time health workers have come under attack. We witnessed the killings of 3 innocent polio workers during the national polio vaccination campaign in March this year [2021] as well. Such senseless violence must stop immediately, and those responsible must be investigated and brought to justice.

The national polio vaccination campaign, which began yesterday [14 Jun 2021], has been suspended in the East region. Polio immunization campaigns are a vital and effective way to reach millions of children to protect them against polio. Depriving children from an assurance of a healthy life is inhumane.

The United Nations strongly condemns all attacks on health workers anywhere. The delivery of health care is impartial and any attack against health workers and those who work to defend them is an attack on the children, whose very lives they are trying to protect.

--
