----
[2B] UN news
Date: Tue 15 Jun 2021
Source: UN News [edited]
https://news.un.org/en/story/2021/06/1094062


Peace and Security
Five health workers carrying out a polio vaccination campaign in Afghanistan's Nangarhar Province were killed on Tuesday [15 Jun 2021], and 4 others injured, during a series of attacks condemned by a senior UN official on the ground as brutal and "senseless."

The UN humanitarian coordination office OCHA, said the deaths and injuries occurred during 5 separate attacks on health workers, the latest in a recent spate that saw 3 health workers killed in March [2021] during the national polio vaccination effort in Nangahar.

Earlier this month [June 2021], humanitarian workers with the Halo Trust demining group came under attack in northern Afghanistan, where extremists from an ISIL affiliate killed 10 and wounded more than a dozen [12], in what the UN Security Council described as an "atrocious and cowardly targeted attack."

The UN Resident and Humanitarian Coordinator in the country, Dr. Ramiz Alakbarov, said that he was "appalled by the brutality of these killings" on Tuesday [15 Jun 2021], adding that "the senseless violence must stop," urging Afghan authorities to bring those responsible to justice.

He said the national campaign, which only began on Monday [14 Jun 2021], aimed at reaching nearly 10 million under-5s, had been suspended in the eastern region. "Polio immunization campaigns are a vital and effective way to reach millions of children...Depriving children from an assurance of a healthy life is inhumane."

An attack on children
"The UN strongly condemns all attacks on health workers anywhere. The delivery of healthcare is impartial, and any attack against health workers and those who work to defend them is an attack on the children, whose very lives they are trying to protect," he added.

The UN extended deepest condolences to the families, friends, and colleagues of those who lost their lives, wishing the injured a full recovery.

Tedros "deeply saddened"
The head of the World Health Organization (WHO), Tedros Adhanom Ghebreyesus, tweeted that he was "deeply saddened" by the attacks, adding that "access to essential health service and immunization campaigns should be unimpeded so that communities can be protected."

According to news reports, Afghanistan reported 56 new cases of polio last year [2020]. But officials have reported that only 1 wild poliovirus case has been detected in the country since October last year [2020].

--
